description:
Cool critter, and first time I'd seen one.  

Being captured by staff as part of the BioBlitz herp walk.  When the lizard saw the loop coming it tried to bite at it, before being lassoed and brought back for show-and-tell.

Didn't notice when we were handling it, but in these photos it has red mites wandering all over it!  I don't think they're parasitic, though, since when looking at the ground they seemed to be wandering all over every thing (and paying particular attention to Desert Five-spot plants).

description:
Edit: I was excited that maybe the egret I saw made these tracks, but it's probably more of a goose that stopped by when the lake was temporarily here. -Edit

Tracks presumably from the Great Egret at the Grandstand, Racetrack Playa, Death Valley National Park. The tracks suggest the bird was here when the playa was wet, though it would find nothing to eat in this lake! iPhone 7 for scale

Or they could be some other bird, like a raven, which maybe is probably more likely. But, it was very unlikely to have a Great Egret flying around the Grandstand on the verge of summer.

See my observation 6440620 for photos of the egret.
This little one was about 8-10" long. I was SUPER excited to see one of these!!! It was pink and black, but I don't know if the pink fades with age?

description: Desert iguana

One of three territorial males on plot. From the Cornell Birds of North America species account:

I. v. auricollis (Deppe, 1830): Also known as Long-tailed Chat. Breeds western portion of range from w. Great Plains (including s. Saskatchewan) and w. Texas westward; winters from s. Baja California, s. Sinaloa, and s. Texas south to Colima, Oaxaca, and central Guatemala. Specimens of vagrants ascribed to this race have been taken as far east as Georgia and Massachusetts (Dunn and Garrett 1997). Upperparts grayer (less greenish) compared with nominate virens, especially crown, wings, and back; malar-feathers mostly white; tail longer than wing (tail averages 6 mm longer, sex for sex, than nominate virens); tendency for males to exhibit deep orange-yellow breast (more frequently yellow, lacking orange tones, in eastern males).
